'''Robert White''' (May 28, 1876 <U+2013> August 15, 1935) was an [[Americans|American]] [[lawyer]] and [[politician]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[West Virginia]]. White served four consecutive terms as the [[Prosecutor|Prosecuting Attorney]] for [[Hampshire County, West Virginia|Hampshire County]] (1912<U+2013>1928) and served one term in the [[West Virginia Senate]] (1930<U+2013>1934) representing the state's Fifteenth Senatorial District in the 40th and 41st Sessions of the [[West Virginia Legislature]]. During the 1933 legislative year, White served as the [[floor leader]] for the [[West Virginia Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] members of the West Virginia Senate. 

White was a member of the White political family of Virginia and West Virginia and was the son of Hampshire County Clerk of Court and West Virginia Fish Commission President [[Christian Streit White]] (1839<U+2013>1917) and the grandson of Hampshire County Clerk of Court [[John Baker White (Virginia)|John Baker White]] (1794<U+2013>1862). White was a nephew of [[List of West Virginia Attorneys General|West Virginia Attorney General]] [[Robert White (politician)|Robert White]] (1833<U+2013>1915).

==Early life and education==
Robert White was born on May 28, 1876 in [[Romney, West Virginia|Romney]], [[West Virginia]].<ref name = "WVDCH1">{{Citation | url = http://www.wvculture.org/vrr/va_bcdetail.aspx?Id=2573074 | title = Birth Record Detail: Robert White | work = West Virginia Vital Research Records | publisher = West Virginia Division of Culture and History | accessdate = November 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name = "WVDCH6">{{Citation | url = http://www.wvculture.org/vrr/va_dcdetail.aspx?Id=1470972 | title = Death Record Detail: Robert White | work = West Virginia Vital Research Records | publisher = West Virginia Division of Culture and History | accessdate = November 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name = "Callahan1">{{Harvnb|Callahan|1923|p=635.}}</ref> He was the second child of [[Hampshire County, West Virginia|Hampshire County]] Clerk of Court [[Christian Streit White]] (1839<U+2013>1917) with his second wife Catharine Steele White (1837<U+2013>1869)<ref name = "WVDCH1"/><ref name = "Callahan1"/> and the third eldest of his father's five children.<ref name = "Callahan1"/> White was a grandson of Hampshire County Clerk of Court [[John Baker White (Virginia)|John Baker White]] (1794<U+2013>1862)<ref name = "Callahan1"/> and a great-grandson of the prominent [[Virginia]] judge [[Robert White (judge)|Robert White]] (1759<U+2013>1831).<ref name = "Callahan1"/> His uncle [[Robert White (politician)|Robert White]] (1833-1915) served as [[List of West Virginia Attorneys General|Attorney General of West Virginia]] and his brother [[John Baker White (West Virginia politician)|John Baker White]] (1868<U+2013>1944) was a [[Officer (armed forces)|military officer]] and later served as a [[Charleston, West Virginia|Charleston]] city councilman and president of the West Virginia Board of Control.

White received his early education in the [[public school]]s of Romney, and attended Romney's Potomac Academy.<ref name = "Callahan1"/> He commenced his career in [[public service]] at the age of 16<ref name = "Callahan1"/> when he began serving as the Deputy Clerk of Court in the office of his father, Christian Streit White, who was then serving as Clerk of Court for Hampshire County.<ref name = "Callahan1"/> In 1894, White graduated from Potomac Academy at the age of 18.<ref name = "Callahan1"/><ref name = "WVBA1">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Bar Association|1935|p=193.}}</ref> Two years later, he began his studying [[jurisprudence]] in the [[West Virginia University College of Law]] in [[Morgantown, West Virginia|Morgantown]].<ref name = "Callahan1"/><ref name = "WVBA1"/> He graduated from the West Virginia University College of Law in 1899,<ref name = "Callahan1"/><ref name = "WVBA1"/><ref name = "WVUAA1">{{Harvnb|West Virginia University Alumni Association|1903|p=199.}}</ref> earning a [[Bachelor of Laws]] [[First professional degree|degree]].<ref name = "WVUAA1"/> White cast his first vote for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] presidential nominee [[William Jennings Bryan]] in the [[United States presidential election, 1900|United States presidential election of 1900]].<ref name = "Callahan1"/>

== Law career ==
Following his graduation in 1899 from [[West Virginia University]],<ref name = "Callahan1"/> White returned to Romney and established a [[practice of law|law practice]].<ref name = "Callahan1"/><ref name = "WVUAA1"/> In 1903, he became associated with his father Christian Streit White in a law practice, following the conclusion of his father's term as Hampshire County Clerk of Court.<ref name = "Callahan1"/> White continued to practice law with his father until 1912, when he was elected to his first term as [[Prosecutor|Prosecuting Attorney]] for Hampshire County.<ref name = "Callahan1"/><ref name = "WVBA1"/>

== Political career ==
Before the age of 21, White represented Hampshire County as a delegate to a [[West Virginia Democratic Party]] state convention.<ref name = "NYT1">{{Citation| last =  | first =  | author-link =| title =Robert White: Former West Virginia State Senator Started Political Career Early | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | publication-place = [[New York City]], [[New York]] | volume = | issue = | date = August 16, 1935 | page = | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30E16F93A59107A93C4A81783D85F418385F9 | accessdate = November 17, 2013}}</ref>

In 1912, won election to serve as the Prosecuting Attorney for Hampshire County.<ref name = "Callahan1"/><ref name = "WVBA1"/> He was elected to the position four times, and served four four-year terms from 1912 to 1928.<ref name = "Callahan1"/><ref name = "WVBA1"/><ref name = "NYT1"/> While serving as the county's prosecuting attorney, White was a strong proponent of the [[Good Roads Movement]]<ref name = "Callahan1"/> and under his leadership, the first [[concrete bridge]] was constructed in Hampshire County by the County Court.<ref name = "Callahan1"/>

Between 1917 and 1921,<ref name = "WVL1">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1917|p=45.}}</ref><ref name = "WVL2">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1918|p=45.}}</ref><ref name = "WVL3">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1921|p=58.}}</ref> in addition to serving as the county's prosecuting attorney, White served as the Commissioner of School Lands<ref name = "WVL1"/><ref name = "WVL2"/><ref name = "WVL3"/> and as one of the Chancery Commissioners for Hampshire County, along with [[Joshua Soule Zimmerman]] and James Sloan Kuykendall.<ref name = "WVL1"/><ref name = "WVL2"/><ref name = "WVL3"/>

In 1930, White was elected to serve in the [[West Virginia Senate]] representing the state's Fifteenth Senatorial District.<ref name = "NYT1"/><ref name = "Munske1">{{Harvnb|Munske|Kerns|2004|p=180.}}</ref><ref name = "WVL4">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|2011|p=434.}}</ref> He served in the 40th and 41st Sessions of the [[West Virginia Legislature]] and completed his term in 1934.<ref name = "Munske1"/><ref name = "WVL4"/><ref name = "WVL5">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|2011|p=423.}}</ref> White served as the [[floor leader]] for the West Virginia Senate's Democratic Party members during the 1933 legislative year.<ref name = "NYT1"/>

== Affiliations ==
White served as a master of the Masonic Lodge,<ref name = "Callahan1"/> and was affiliated with the Odd Fellows.<ref name = "Callahan1"/>

